{"questionId":"21449","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A garden has a triangular sunshade suspended from three points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext><mo>(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math>, relative to an origin in the corner of the garden. All distances are measured&nbsp;in metres.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence find the area of the triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABC</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>area is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msqrt><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>24</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mtext>m</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3693</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>17</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21449","referenceCode":"21M.1.AHL.TZ1.5c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence find the area of the triangle ABC.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.10—Vector definitions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}